#------------------------------------------------------------------------------#
# FILE: alarm_config.lst
#
# DESCRIPTION:
#
# File to define an optional list of alarm buckets for particular opcodes.
# This can be used in cases where we would like to know more about the cases
# where different opcodes take an unexpectedly long time to execut.
#
# The opcodes should be listed one per line and can be either the numeric value
# or name. They are followed by a list of range delimeters (in seconds). The
# special value '*' can be used to define a default set of buckets for all
# opcodes (which allows a global general alarm to be applied as an alternative
# to the PERFLIB_ALARM parameter - which is mutually exclusive with this one).
#
# There is currently a limit of 8 buckets per opcode.
#
# In addition to the time, each bucket specifies an additional set of flag
# attributes, flist size and a 'severity' description. The flags control
# behaviour of the alarms whilst the 'severity' description is informational
# to be reported in the alarm (e.g. one my indicate an opcode that took 10
# seconds to execute as WARNING, whilst one that took more than 20 seconds
# might be CRITICAL). For logging flists, a maximum size can be configured
# to avoid logging huge flists in alarms.
#
# So a full bucket definition is defined as follows (comma-separated):
#
#    <limit>,<flags>[<size>],<severity>
#
# The flag values that can be set are:
#
#    Flist logging flags
#    -------------------
#    - (minus)    : alarm will be logged, but no flists.
#    + (plus)     : alarm will be logged with top-level opcode input flist
#    * (asterisk) : alarm will be logged with all opcode input flists
#
#    Size
#    ----
#    nnn          : number of bytes to limit flist size to (0 or missing will
#                   cause full flists to be recorded).
#
#    Alarm Behaviour
#    ---------------
#    r or R       : alarm will fire repeatedly at this interval (this can only
#                   be defined on the last bucket).
#
# There may be up to 8 buckets, each separated by space on the same line for
# each opcode.
#
# E.g. a configuration for an alarm bucket which logged at 10.0 sconds and
# 20.0 seconds (recurring) might look like:
#
#   10.0,+1024,WARNING   20.0,*R2048,CRITICAL
#
# INFORMATION:
#
# BRM performance tracing library ...
#
# REVISION:
#
# $Revision: 1.2 $
# $Author: ihargrea $
# $Date: 2016/11/04 21:12:07 $
#------------------------------------------------------------------------------#
#
# Example defining two alarms for a custom opcode with no limits on flist size.
#
PCM_OP_IAN_POL_SLOW_OPCODE 10.0,+,WARNING 20.0,*,CRITICAL
#
# Example defining an alarm with a recurring last bucket ... an alarm will be
# raised every 20 seconds until the opcode finally finishes. No limit on flist
# sizes.
#
PCM_OP_CUST_COMMIT_CUSTOMER 5.0,+WARNING  10.0,*,SEVERE 20,*R,CRITICAL
#
# A catch-all alarm for all other opcodes. This will log only th input flist
# and a maximum of 1024 characters.
#
* 2.0,+1024,INFO
